  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Can you get messenger bot to upload images?",
  "response": "Yes, you can configure a Messenger bot to upload images. This involves integrating your bot with the Facebook Graph API or using a third-party bot development platform that supports image handling.\n\nHere's a general approach to get a Messenger bot to upload images:\n\n### Using Facebook Graph API\n\n1. **Set up a Facebook App**: Create a new app on the [Facebook Developer portal](https://developers.facebook.com/) if you haven't already. Ensure you have access to the Messenger API.\n\n2. **Get Page Access Token**: Obtain your page access token to authenticate API requests. This can be done via your Facebook App settings under *Messenger*.\n\n3. **Configure Webhook**: Set up a webhook to receive events/messages from Facebook Messenger. You'll need to set up an endpoint on your server to handle incoming messages and respond accordingly.\n\n4. **Send Image Messages**: Use the Graph API to send image messages from your bot. Here's a basic example using a POST request:\n\n```json\nPOST https://graph.facebook.com/v11.0/me/messages?access_token=<PAGE_ACCESS_TOKEN>\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{\n  \"recipient\": {\n    \"id\": \"<RECIPIENT_ID>\"\n  },\n  \"message\": {\n    \"attachment\": {\n      \"type\": \"image\",\n      \"payload\": {\n        \"url\": \"<IMAGE_URL>\",\n        \"is_reusable\": true // if you want to reuse the image\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Using Bot Development Platforms\n\n#### Chatfuel\n\n1. **Create a Bot in Chatfuel**: Sign up and create a bot.\n2. **Add a Block**: Add a new block to the flow where you want to send an image.\n3. **Add Gallery Card or Image Block**: Use the Gallery Card block to send an image by uploading the image or providing a URL.\n4. **Publish Your Bot**: Save and publish your bot.\n\n#### ManyChat\n\n1. **Set Up ManyChat**: Sign up and connect your Facebook page.\n2. **Create Content Block**: Create a new content block within a flow where the bot will send the image.\n3. **Image Element**: Use the image element to upload an image or provide a URL.\n4. **Publish Your Bot**: Deploy and publish the changes.\n\n### Sending Images Programmatically with Node.js\n\nHere's an example using Node.js and `axios` to send an image via the Facebook Graph API:\n\n```javascript\nconst axios = require('axios');\n\nconst PAGE_ACCESS_TOKEN = 'your_page_access_token';\n\nconst sendImageMessage = async (recipientId, imageUrl) => {\n  const url = `https://graph.facebook.com/v11.0/me/messages?access_token=${PAGE_ACCESS_TOKEN}`;\n  \n  const messageData = {\n    recipient: { id: recipientId },\n    message: {\n      attachment: {\n        type: 'image',\n        payload: { url: imageUrl, is_reusable: true }\n      }\n    }\n  };\n\n  try {\n    await axios.post(url, messageData);\n    console.log('Image sent successfully');\n  } catch (error) {\n    console.error('Error sending image: ', error);\n  }\n};\n\n// Example usage\nsendImageMessage('<RECIPIENT_ID>', '<IMAGE_URL>');\n```\n\nMake sure to replace the placeholders (`<PAGE_ACCESS_TOKEN>`, `<RECIPIENT_ID>`, `<IMAGE_URL>`) with actual values for your setup.\n\nBy following these steps, you can successfully get your Messenger bot to upload and send images to users.",
